docs.abstract: The Salesforce C.E.O.’s planned acquisition of Slack will have him competing directly with the Goliath that is Microsoft.
docs.snippet: The Salesforce C.E.O.’s planned acquisition of Slack will have him competing directly with the Goliath that is Microsoft.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Five years ago, Marc Benioff negotiated to sell Salesforce, the software company he co-founded in 1999 and has run ever since, to Microsoft. If the deal had gone through, he would have been richly rewarded — but, in the end, just another employee of the tech colossus.

headline.main: Marc Benioff Sets His Sights on Microsoft

docs.abstract: The person writing the check is still the most important customer.
docs.snippet: The person writing the check is still the most important customer.

docs.abstract: The move caps an acquisitive streak by Salesforce and ends Slack’s run as an independent publicly traded company.
docs.snippet: The move caps an acquisitive streak by Salesforce and ends Slack’s run as an independent publicly traded company.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Salesforce said on Tuesday that it would buy the workplace software company Slack for $27.7 billion in cash and stock, the latest in a wave of deals as the coronavirus pandemic boosts demand for tools that enable people to work remotely.

headline.main: Salesforce to Acquire Slack for $27.7 Billion
headline.print_headline: Salesforce  To Spend  $27.7 Billion  To Buy Slack

byline.original: By Erin Griffith and Lauren Hirsch
